## Why This Is Asked
This problem tests understanding of dynamic programming with non-overlapping segments where the segment value has a quadratic structure. It challenges candidates to handle state transitions, reconstruction, and complexity analysis systematically.

## Key Concepts
- DP over prefix arrays with block count tracking
- Transition by considering all possible block endpoints
- Prefix sum optimization for O(1) subarray sum queries
- Backpointers for optimal solution reconstruction
- Time-space trade-off analysis

## Code Implementation
```javascript
function maxSubarrayValue(A, k) {
  const n = A.length;
  const prefix = new Array(n + 1).fill(0);
  for (let i = 0; i < n; i++) {
    prefix[i + 1] = prefix[i] + A[i];
  }

  const dp = Array(n + 1).fill().map(() => Array(k + 1).fill(-Infinity));
  const prevStart = Array(n + 1).fill().map(() => Array(k + 1).fill(-1));
  dp[0][0] = 0;

  for (let i = 1; i <= n; i++) {
    for (let t = 1; t <= k; t++) {
      // Skip i
      if (dp[i-1][t] > dp[i][t]) {
        dp[i][t] = dp[i-1][t];
        prevStart[i][t] = prevStart[i-1][t];
      }

      // End block at i
      for (let j = 1; j <= i; j++) {
        const blockValue = (prefix[i] - prefix[j-1]) * (i-j+1);
        const candidate = dp[j-1][t-1] + blockValue;
        if (candidate > dp[i][t]) {
          dp[i][t] = candidate;
          prevStart[i][t] = j;
        }
      }
    }
  }

  // Reconstruction
  const result = [];
  let currI = n, currT = k;
  while (currT > 0 && currI > 0) {
    const start = prevStart[currI][currT];
    if (start !== -1 && start !== prevStart[currI-1][currT]) {
      result.unshift([start-1, currI-1]);
      currI = start - 1;
      currT--;
    } else {
      currI--;
    }
  }

  return { maxValue: dp[n][k], subarrays: result };
}
```

